+    <blockquote>
+        <p>
+            Nmap is a <abbr lang="de">FHEM</abbr> module to perform network scans with Nmap
+            and display its results and further informations.
+        </p>
+        <p>
+            If a new device is detected, Nmap generates an event, similar to this example:
+            <br>
+            <code><var>devicename</var> new host: <var>hostname</var> (<var>IPv4</var>)</code>
+        </p>
+        <p>
+            If a already by <abbr lang="en">MAC</abbr> address known device got a new
+            <abbr lang="en">IPv4</abbr> address, Nmap generates an event, similar to this example:
+            <br>
+            <code><var>devicename</var> new <abbr>IP</abbr>: <var>hostname</var> (<var>IPv4</var>)</code>
+        </p>
+
+        <h4>
+            Prerequisites
+        </h4>
+        <blockquote>
+            <p>
+                To use Nmap, the program <kbd>nmap</kbd> and the Perl module <kbd><span lang="en">Nmap::Parser</span></kbd> are required.
+            </p>
+            <p>
+                On Debian based operating systems these can be installed via
+            </p>
+            <p>
+                <code>apt-get install nmap libnmap-parser-perl</code> (to Debian Stretch),
+                <br>
+                or
+                <br>
+                <code>apt install nmap libnmap-parser-perl</code> (after Debian Stretch).
+            </p>
+        </blockquote>
+
+        <a name="Nmapdefine"></a>
+        <h4 id="Nmapdefine">
+            Define
+        </h4>
+        <blockquote>
+            <p>
+                <code>define <var>devicename</var> Nmap <var>target specification</var></code>
+            </p>
+            <dl>
+                <dt>
+                    <var>target specification</var>
+                </dt>
+                <dd>
+                    <p>
+                        Target hosts to be scanned.
+                    </p>
+                    <p>
+                        The simplest case is the description of an <abbr lang="en">IPv4</abbr> destination address or a target host name for scanning.
+                    </p>
+                    <p>
+                        To scan an entire network of neighboring hosts, Nmap supports <abbr lang="en"
+                        title="Classless Interdomain Routing">CIDR</abbr> style addresses. <var>/numbits</var>
+                        can be appended to an <abbr lang="en">IPv4</abbr> address or to a hostname. Nmap will scan all
+                        <abbr lang="en">IPv4</abbr> addresses where the first <var>numbits</var> match those of the
+                        given <abbr lang="en">IPv4</abbr> address or host name.
+                    </p>
+                    <p>
+                        The <var>target specification</var> <var>192.168.10.0/24</var> would address 256 hosts
+                        from 192.168.10.0 to 192.168.10.255. Even so <var>192.168.10.40/24</var>.
+                    </p>
+                    <p>
+                        It's also possible to scan multiple networks at the same time.
+                        For example <var>192.168.1.0/24 192.168.2.0/24</var> would scan the 512 hosts between 192.168.1.0 and 192.168.2.255.
+                    </p>
+                    <p>
+                        See also <a href="https://nmap.org/man/de/man-target-specification.html">Nmap Man Page (Specifying Destinations)</a>.
+                    </p>
+                </dd>
+            </dl>
+        </blockquote>
+
+        <a name="Nmapset"></a>
+        <h4 id="Nmapset">
+            Set
+        </h4>
+        <blockquote>
+            <dl>
+                <dt><p><code>clear readings</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Deletes all readings except <var>state</var>.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>deleteOldReadings <var>t</var></code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Deletes all readings older than <code><var>t</var></code> seconds.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>interrupt</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Aborts a running scan.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>statusRequest</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Start a new network scan.
+                </dd>
+            </dl>
+        </blockquote>
+
+
+        <a name="Nmapreadings"></a>
+        <h4 id="Nmapreadings">
+            Readings
+        </h4>
+        <blockquote>
+            <h5>General readings</h5>
+
+            <dl>
+                <dt><p><code>NmapVersion</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Version of the installed Nmap executable.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>hostsScanned</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Quantity of scanned hosts.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>hostsUp</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Quantity of available hosts.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>knownHosts</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Quantity of known hosts.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>scanDuration</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Duration in seconds of the last scan.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>state</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    <dl>
+                        <dt><p><code>initialized</code></p></dt>
+                        <dd>
+                            Device was initialized oder (re-)enabled.
+                        </dd>
+
+                        <dt><p><code>running</code></p></dt>
+                        <dd>
+                            Running network scan.
+                        </dd>
+
+                        <dt><p><code>done</code></p></dt>
+                        <dd>
+                            Network scan was successful completed.
+                        </dd>
+
+                        <dt><p><code>aborted</code></p></dt>
+                        <dd>
+                            Network scan was aborted by the user or encountered a time out.
+                        </dd>
+
+                        <dt><p><code>disabled</code></p></dt>
+                        <dd>
+                            Device was deactivated.
+                        </dd>
+                    </dl>
+                </dd>
+            </dl>
+
+            <h5><span lang="en">Host</span> specific <span lang="en">readings</span></h5>
+            <p>
+                See the <code>metaReading</code> attribute below for the value of <var>identifier</var>.
+            </p>
+            <dl>
+                <dt><p><code><var>identifier</var>_alias</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Alias ​​which is specified under the attribute <var>devAlias</var> for the network device.
+                    If no alias is specified, the hostname is displayed.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code><var>identifier</var>_hostname</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Hostname of the network device. If this can not be determined, the IPv4 address is displayed.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code><var>identifier</var>_ip</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    <abbr lang="en">IPv4</abbr> address of the network device.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code><var>identifier</var>_lastSeen</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Timestamp at which the network device was last seen.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code><var>identifier</var>_macAddress</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    <abbr lang="en">MAC</abbr> address of the network device (can only be determined if the scan is executed with root privileges).
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code><var>identifier</var>_macVendor</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Presumed vendor of the network device, based on the <abbr lang="en">MAC</abbr> address (can only be determined if the scan is executed with root privileges).
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code><var>identifier</var>_state</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    State of the network device, values <var>absent</var> and <var>present</var>.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code><var>identifier</var>_uptime</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Duration in seconds since the network device is reachable.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code><var>identifier</var>_uptimeText</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Duration in
+                    <var>d</var> <span lang="en">days</span>,
+                    <var>hh</var> <span lang="en">hours</span>, <var>mm</var> <span lang="en">minutes</span>, <var>ss</var> <span lang="en">seconds</span>,
+                    since the network device is reachable.
+                </dd>
+            </dl>
+        </blockquote>
+
+        <a name="Nmapattr"></a>
+        <h4 id="Nmapattr">
+            Attributes
+        </h4>
+        <blockquote>
+            <dl>
+                <dt><p><code>absenceThreshold <var>n</var></code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    <p>
+                        The number of network cans that must result in <var>absent</var> before the state
+                        of a network device changes to <var>absent</var>. This could be used to verify the
+                        absence of a device.
+                    </p>
+                    <p>
+                        If this attribute is set to a value &gt;1, <var>state</var> remains on <var>present</var>,
+                        until the status changes final to <var>absent</var>.
+                    </p>
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>args <var>args</var></code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Arguments passed to <kbd>nmap</kbd> for scanning. Defaults to <code><var>-sn</var></code>
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>deleteOldReadings <var>t</var></code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    After a network scan, all host-specific readings older than <var>t</var> seconds are deleted.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt>
+                    <p>
+                        <code>
+                            devAlias    <var>id<sub>1</sub></var>:<var>alias<sub>1</sub></var>
+                                        <var>id<sub>2</sub></var>:<var>alias<sub>2</sub></var>
+                                        &hellip;
+                                        <var>id<sub>n</sub></var>:<var>alias<sub>n</sub></var>
+                        </code>
+                    </p>
+                </dt>
+                <dd>
+                    <p>
+                        A whitespace separated list of <var>id</var>:<var>alias</var> pairs that can be used to give an alias to network devices.
+                    </p>
+                    <p>
+                        <var>id</var> can be a <abbr lang="en">MAC</abbr> address, hostname or <abbr lang="en">IPv4</abbr> address.
+                    </p>
+                    <p><strong>Examples</strong></p>
+                    <dl>
+                        <dt><p><abbr lang="en">MAC</abbr>-Adresse</p></dt>
+                        <dd>
+                            <code>attr <var>devicename</var> devAlias 5C:51:88:A5:94:1F:Michaels_Mobile_byMAC</code>.
+                        </dd>
+
+                        <dt><p lang="en">Hostname</p></dt>
+                        <dd>
+                            <code>attr <var>devicename</var> devAlias android-87c7a6221093d830:Michaels_Mobile_byHOST</code>.
+                        </dd>
+
+                        <dt><p><abbr lang="en">IPv4</abbr>-Adresse</p></dt>
+                        <dd>
+                            <code>attr <var>devicename</var> devAlias 192.168.1.130:Michaels_Mobile_byIP</code>.
+                        </dd>
+                    </dl>
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>disable 1</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    A running scan is canceled and no new scans are started
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>excludeHosts <var>target specification</var></code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    All target hosts in the <var>target specification</var> are skipped during the scan
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>interval <var>t</var></code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Interval in seconds in which the scan is performed. Default is <var>900</var> seconds, minimum is <var>30</var>.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>keepReadings 1</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    If a new <abbr lang="en">IPv4</abbr> address is recognized for a device with a known
+                    <abbr lang="en">MAC</abbr> address, the invalid readings are deleted unless this attribute is set.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>leadingZeros 1</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    <p>
+                        At the host specific readings, the <abbr lang="en">IPv4</abbr> address octets are prefixed with
+                        zeros so that are three digits in every octet.
+                    </p>
+                    <p>
+                        For example, <var>192.168.0.1</var> will be displayed as <var>192.168.000.001</var> if
+                        <code>leadingZeros</code> is set to 1.
+                    </p>
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>metaReading <var>metaReading</var></code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    <p>
+                        Which <var>identifier</var> is used as prefix for the host specific readings. The options
+                        <var>alias</var>, <var>hostname</var>, <var>ip</var> oder <var>macAddress</var> are available.
+                        Default is <var>ip</var>.
+                    </p>
+                    <p>
+                        <var>macAddress</var> is only available, if root privileges are given. If set and root privileges are not available, <var>ip</var> is used instead.
+                    </p>
+                    <p>
+                        After changing this attribute to another value, the readings must be cleared manually and a new scan must be started.
+                    </p>
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>path</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    Path to the <kbd>nmap</kbd> executable. Default is <var>/urs/bin/nmap</var>.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>readingFnAttributes</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    See <a href="#readingFnAttributes">readingFnAttributes</a>.
+                </dd>
+
+                <dt><p><code>sudo 1</code></p></dt>
+                <dd>
+                    <p>Run scan as user <kbd>root</kbd></p>
+                    <p>
+                        To do this, the <abbr lang="en">FHEM</abbr> requires root privileges or is allowed to impersonate root via <kbd>sudo</kbd>. See <kbd>man sudo</kbd>
+                        for further system dependend informations.
+                    </p>
+                </dd>
+            </dl>
+        </blockquote>
+    </blockquote>
